<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    Building the <a href="/backlog/2505-/">plateau console board</a> (#2505 — the lane build-status board) surfaced a
    set of candidate low-level UI primitives. <a href="/backlog/2533-console-board-derived-ui-standards/">#2533</a>
    decides, per candidate, whether it earns a <strong>Web Everything standard</strong> (mint), <strong>extends</strong>
    an existing one, <strong>parks</strong>, or stays <strong>app-custom</strong>. The bar for minting is a
    <strong>second consumer beyond this one board</strong> — a standard exists to be reused across independent parties,
    so a helper reused three ways <em>inside one board</em> is app architecture, not a standard. This topic surveys the
    four live primitives against real prior art so each fork rests on grounding, not assertion.
</p>

<h2>1 — Shared quantitative axis (the <code>scale-ruler</code>)</h2>
<p>
    The board maps a scalar to a <strong>length or position on one labeled axis</strong>, with an aggregate: a card's
    height encodes its size, its horizon-crossing encodes its proven fraction, and a lane's stacked heights read as its
    ETA (<code>1pt &approx; 9min &approx; 17px</code>). The recurring kernel across the prior art is
    <strong>scale + ticks + aggregate</strong>:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>d3-scale</strong> — <code>scaleLinear().domain([…]).range([…])</code> with <code>.ticks()</code> /
        <code>.tickFormat()</code> is the reusable value&rarr;pixel kernel behind <code>d3-axis</code>; d3 deliberately
        ships the <em>scale</em> as a standalone module separate from the axis <em>rendering</em>.</li>
    <li><strong>Vega-Lite encodings</strong> — a scalar bound to the <code>size</code>, <code>x</code>, or <code>y</code>
        channel over a shared scale is exactly "a value on a labeled axis"; the board's residue is Vega-Lite's encoding
        <em>minus the marks / chart grammar</em>.</li>
    <li><strong>Native CSS</strong> — <code>&lt;progress value max&gt;</code> and <code>aspect-ratio</code> both derive a
        length directly from a value with no library.</li>
    <li><strong>Gantt / treemap size encodings</strong> — duration&rarr;bar-width, quantity&rarr;area: the same
        scalar-to-extent mapping in scheduling and hierarchy visualisations.</li>
    <li><strong>CSS scroll-driven animations</strong> — scroll position &harr; a normalised 0&ndash;1 progress
        (<code>animation-timeline: scroll()</code>): the platform's own "position is a value on an axis" primitive.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    <strong>Delta vs WE today:</strong> <a href="/projects/webcharts/">Web Charts</a> (#105) already owns the Vega-Lite
    L1 grammar and its <code>size</code>/positional encodings; the only residue is a <em>bare labeled axis without a
    chart</em>. That residue graduates to a Web Charts extension when a genuine off-board consumer appears — not a new
    standalone primitive on one board's evidence.
</p>

<h2>2 — Dual / multi-track progress (claimed vs proven)</h2>
<p>
    Board cards show <strong>two</strong> fractions on one bar: the agent's plan claim and the spec-proven amount. Prior
    art for two values on one track:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>CI / build UIs</strong> — planned-vs-actual and estimated-vs-real step bars (GitHub Actions, Buildkite)
        routinely overlay a target on the live fill.</li>
    <li><strong>Media buffering</strong> — the native <code>&lt;video&gt;</code> / download-manager pattern of a
        <em>buffered</em> track behind the <em>played</em> track is the canonical "second value on the same scale."</li>
</ul>
<p>
    <strong>Delta vs WE today:</strong> the <a href="/intents/progress/">progress</a> intent is deliberately
    <strong>thin</strong> (ratified <a href="/backlog/1469-/">#1469</a>): it adopts the native <code>&lt;progress&gt;</code>
    contract verbatim and names <code>loader.progress</code> and <a href="/intents/flow-progress/">flow-progress</a> as
    <em>consumers that compose it</em>, not sub-types. Two completion magnitudes are therefore <strong>two composed
    progress readouts</strong>, and rendering them as one overlaid track is a <em>presentation</em> concern (presentation
    is a dimension, not a home — <a href="/docs/agent/platform-decisions.md#readout-placement-by-value-type">readout-placement-by-value-type</a>).
    "Claimed vs verified" is moreover a <strong>data-provenance / trust</strong> distinction, not a completion magnitude —
    if it needs a standard home that home is provenance/audit, never a second track bolted onto <code>progress</code>.
</p>

<h2>3 — Semantic zoom / level-of-detail</h2>
<p>
    The board's L0&rarr;L3 (constellation tiles &rarr; lane board &rarr; gate checklist &rarr; build inspector) is a zoom
    where <strong>each level swaps representation</strong> rather than scaling one view. Prior art:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Pad++ / Jazz</strong> and <strong>Microsoft DeepZoom / Seadragon</strong> — continuous multiscale
        surfaces where the drawn content changes with scale (semantic zoom, not just geometric).</li>
    <li><strong>Data-viz semantic zoom</strong> — Kibana/Elastic and Datashader swap aggregation/representation by zoom
        level.</li>
    <li><strong>IDE minimaps / code folding</strong> — a compressed representation of the same document at low detail.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    <strong>Delta vs WE today:</strong> <a href="/intents/viewport-transform/">viewport-transform</a> owns
    <em>geometric</em> pan/zoom and explicitly disclaims representation; <a href="/intents/hierarchy/">hierarchy</a> owns
    tree traversal. Neither owns representational LOD. But "each level is a different view" is <strong>routing +
    density/responsive rendering</strong> the platform already provides (navigation + <a href="/intents/density/">density</a>);
    the only non-trivial residue is a "floor of signals that must survive every level," and one board wanting it is not a
    second consumer. App-custom is the un-beaten null hypothesis.
</p>

<h2>4 — Threshold-region overlay (the horizon mask)</h2>
<p>
    The board draws <strong>one datum line across all columns</strong> plus a region treatment
    (<code>backdrop-filter: grayscale</code>) rendering the "past" side as history. Prior art is a single reference datum
    drawn across a multi-column surface:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Gantt "today" line</strong> — a vertical now-marker across every task row.</li>
    <li><strong>Burndown target / ideal line</strong> — a reference trajectory drawn over the actual.</li>
    <li><strong>Kanban WIP-limit lines</strong> — a per-column threshold marker.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    <strong>Delta vs WE today:</strong> the datum line <em>is a tick on the axis</em> of primitive&nbsp;1, and the
    grayscale-past is region <strong>styling</strong> (app CSS / theming), not a contract. It is not separable from the
    axis into a standard of its own, and it too has no off-board second consumer.
</p>

<h2>Classification summary (grounding for #2533)</h2>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Primitive</th><th>Nearest WE owner</th><th>Verdict</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr><td>Shared quantitative axis (scale-ruler)</td><td>Web Charts (Vega-Lite encodings)</td><td>App-custom now; axis-without-marks residue = a Web Charts extension when a 2nd consumer appears.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dual-track progress</td><td>progress intent (thin, #1469)</td><td>Compose two <code>progress</code> readouts + FUI overlay presentation; don't extend. Provenance is a separate home.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Semantic zoom / LOD</td><td>viewport-transform / navigation / density</td><td>App-custom (routing + density); no intent, no 2nd consumer.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Threshold-region overlay</td><td>the axis + CSS</td><td>App-custom; datum = an axis tick, mask = CSS. Not a separable standard.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Swimlane / span-layout</td><td>Web Graph + CSS Grid</td><td>App-custom; name the lane-assignment/docking residue as a future Web Graph extension.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>
<p>
    The through-line: <strong>mint nothing on one board's evidence.</strong> Every candidate either composes an existing
    standard or is app architecture; three residues (a Web Charts axis extension, a Web Graph lane-docking constraint, a
    provenance home for claimed-vs-verified) become graduation candidates when a genuine second consumer surfaces.
</p>

